# Clean Code Principles

## Core Principles
- Follow Tell don't ask - prefer telling objects what to do rather than asking for data and making decisions outside
- Follow Demeter's Law - avoid exposing internal details of objects and prefer high-level interactions
- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) - avoid code duplication
- Follow KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid) - prefer simple solutions over complex ones
- Follow YAGNI (You Aren't Gonna Need It) - don't add functionality until it's needed
- Write code that is easy to read and understand
- Code should be self-documenting through clear naming
- Functions should do one thing and do it well
- Avoid magic numbers and strings - use named constants
- Keep functions small (ideally under 40 lines)
- Reduce complexity and cognitive load
- Use early returns to avoid ELSE statements and reduce nesting

## Code Quality
- Write self-documenting code with clear naming
- Keep functions and methods small and focused
- Minimize cyclomatic complexity
- Avoid deep nesting (max 3-4 levels)
- Use early returns to reduce nesting
- Remove dead code and commented-out code

## Naming Conventions
- Use descriptive names that reveal intent
- Avoid abbreviations unless they're widely understood
- Use verbs for functions/methods, nouns for classes/variables
- Boolean variables should be questions: `isValid`, `hasPermission`
- Collections should be plural: `users`, `items`

## Organization
- Group related functionality together
- Separate concerns (business logic, data access, presentation)
- Use appropriate design patterns when they add clarity
- Research about design patterns in https://refactoring.guru/design-patterns/php
- Avoid premature optimization
- Refactor when code smells appear

## Comments
- Code should be self-explanatory; comments should explain "why", not "what"
- Remove commented-out code before committing
- Use comments for complex business logic or non-obvious decisions
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes

## Error Handling
- Handle errors explicitly
- Use appropriate error types
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Fail fast and fail clearly
- Log errors appropriately

## Design Patterns
- Use design patterns when they add clarity and solve real problems
- Don't over-engineer; apply patterns judiciously
- Prefer composition over inheritance
- Use dependency injection for loose coupling
- Apply factory pattern for object creation when appropriate
- Use repository pattern for data access abstraction

## Performance
- Profile before optimizing; measure, don't guess
- Avoid premature optimization
- Use appropriate data structures and algorithms
- Cache expensive operations when appropriate
- Optimize database queries (avoid N+1 problems)
- Use lazy loading where appropriate
